ons of the Gothic from a wide variety of perspectivesThe Gothic in all its artistic forms and ramifications is traced from the medieval to the twenty-first century. From architecture, painting and sculpture through music, ballet, opera and dance to installation art and the graphic novel, each of the 33 chapters reflects on and weighs in on the ways in which the Gothic is taken up in the art forms and modes under examination. An Introduction discusses Gothic as a changing cultural form across the centuries with deep psychological roots. This is followed by sections on: architectural arts; the visual arts; music and the performance arts; the literary arts; and media and cultural arts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aAncuta, Katarzyna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeville, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlake, Linnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloom, Clive, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBork, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruhm, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuggett, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElferen, Isabella Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElliott, Kamilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFall, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález, Antonio Alcalá, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaefele-Thomas, Ardel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHogle, Jerrold E., econtributor.4c